A neural network is a machine learning model inspired by the way biological neurons work in the brain. 
It consists of interconnected nodes (neurons) organized into layers that learn patterns from data.

Basic Structure:-
         Input Layer → Hidden Layer(s) → Output Layer
Input layer: Receives data (e.g., image pixels, text features).
Hidden layers: Process information through weighted connections and activation functions.
Output layer: Produces predictions or classifications.

How It Works
     Each neuron:
     Receives inputs.
     Multiplies them by weights.
     Adds a bias.
     Applies an activation function.
     Passes the result to the next layer.

Learning Process
     Neural networks learn by:
     Making predictions.
     Comparing predictions to actual results using a loss function.
     Adjusting weights via backpropagation and gradient descent.
     Repeating this process over many examples.
Common Types
     Feedforward Neural Networks (FNN): Basic architecture.
     Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN): Image recognition.
     Recurrent Neural Networks (RNN): Sequential data such as text and speech.
     Transformers: Modern architecture used in large language models like ChatGPT.



